T1  - Procyclical Leverage and Value-at-Risk
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hht068
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
SP  - 373
EP  - 403
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The availability of credit varies over the business cycle through shifts in the leverage of financial intermediaries. Empirically, we find that intermediary leverage is negatively aligned with the banks' Value-at-Risk (VaR). Motivated by the evidence, we explore a contracting model that captures the observed features. Under general conditions on the outcome distribution given by extreme value theory (EVT), intermediaries maintain a constant probability of default to shifts in the outcome distribution, implying substantial deleveraging during downturns. For some parameter values, we can solve the model explicitly, thereby endogenizing the VaR threshold probability from the contracting problem.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hht068
ER  - 



